 <fr:p>We must check that for every <fr:tex>b:B</fr:tex>, the <fr:link
href="erct-001Q.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001Q">fiber</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> at <fr:tex>b</fr:tex> is a <fr:link
href="erct-001I.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001I">proposition</fr:link>. Fixing <fr:tex>u_0,u_1: \mathsf {fiber} \, f \, b</fr:tex> we must check that <fr:tex>u_0=u_1</fr:tex>. We let <fr:tex>\mathopen {} \left ( a_0,p_0 \right ) \mathclose {} \equiv  u_0</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>\mathopen {} \left ( a_1,p_1 \right ) \mathclose {} \equiv  u_1</fr:tex> so that we have <fr:tex>p_0 \colon  fa_0=b</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>p_1 \colon  fa_1=b</fr:tex>. Invoking the <fr:link
href="erct-0010.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-0010">path object</fr:link> structure on <fr:link
href="erct-001Q.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001Q">fibers</fr:link> (<fr:ref
addr="erct-001R"
href="erct-001R.xml"
taxon="Example"></fr:ref>), it suffices to exhibit the following data:</fr:p>
 <fr:tex
display="block">    \begin {aligned}     \phi &amp; \colon  a_0 = a_1 \\      \psi &amp; \colon  p_0 =  \mathsf {act}_{ f } \phi \cdot  p_1    \end {aligned}  </fr:tex>

  <fr:p>As <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> is an <fr:link
href="erct-001K.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001K">embedding</fr:link>, the map <fr:tex>\mathsf {act}_{ f } \colon  a_0 = a_1  \to  fa_0 = fa_1</fr:tex> has an <fr:link
href="erct-000W.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-000W">inverse</fr:link> <fr:tex>\mathopen {} \left ( \mathsf {act}_{ f } ^{-1} , \epsilon , \eta , \chi \right ) \mathclose {}</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Let <fr:tex>\alpha   \colon  fa_0 = fa_1</fr:tex> be the concatenation <fr:tex>p_0 \cdot  p_1 ^{-1}</fr:tex>. Therefore we may define:</fr:p>

 <fr:tex
display="block">    \begin {aligned}     \phi &amp; \colon  a_0 = a_1 \\      \phi &amp;: \equiv   \mathsf {act}_{ f } ^{-1}   \alpha     \end {aligned}  </fr:tex>

 <fr:p>To define <fr:tex>\psi   \colon  p_0= \mathsf {act}_{ f } \phi \cdot  p_1</fr:tex> we use the counit of our <fr:link
href="erct-000W.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-000W">inverse</fr:link> as we have <fr:tex>\epsilon   \alpha   \colon   \mathsf {act}_{ f } \phi  = p_0 \cdot  p_1 ^{-1}</fr:tex>. Thus concatenating on either side with <fr:tex>p_1</fr:tex> we have our goal, modulo the laws of identification concatenation and symmetry respectively.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
